e Arab Spring -- tPart Three: User-Generated Content Journalism around the World -- t10 User-Generated Content Narrates #ForaTemer on Twitter: Patterns of Citizen Media as Users Document an Anti-impeachment Protest in Brazil -- t11 Making Room for Citizen Journalism against User-Generated Content: Situating South Korea’s OhmyNews in the History of Journalism -- t12 Media and User-Generated Content Images during the Terrorist Attacks in Catalonia: Recommendations and Remediation -- t13 What’s Trending? The Influence of Twitter and Instagram Agendas on Online News Portals in Ghana -- t14 We Are Not Parasites: Intergroup Differentiation in the User-Generated Content of Nigerian News Media -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNews coverage today is an emerging collaboration between the general public and professional journalists. News consumers have come to expect and demand the unprecedented immediacy of experience and coverage of breaking news offered by photographs, video clips, audio recordings, tweets, commentary: content created by ordinary citizens. The use of user-generated content is a salient aspect of how journalists and news organizations are responding to technological changes in the twenty-first century.Eyewitness Textures examines the far-reaching changes in journalism spurred by the growing importance of user-generated content. Bringing together the voices and experiences of professional journalists and academic researchers from across five continents, this collection explores news production practices, changing skills among editors and journalists, and corporate and newsroom restructuring. Chapters by practitioners collectively reflect the newsroom experiences of major global media organizations, while the academic contributions address issues of industrial transformation, political influence, truth and verification, aesthetics, and ideological implications. Both perspectives combine to deepen our understanding of what constitutes the conditions and creation of good journalism, as well as the implications of how the profession should be taught to future journalists.Tracing recent shifts in journalism practice around the world, Eyewitness Textures examines the creative adaptation and strategies of journalists and news organizations in the face of transformative technological change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aJournalismxTechnological innovations. 0aJournalism-Technological innovations. 0aUser-generated content. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aArab Spring.  aBBC.  aCBC.  aFrance 24.  aInstagram.  aOhMyNews.  aSpain.  aStoryful.  aTwitter.  aamateur video.  acommunication studies.  adigital witnessing.  aglobal.  ajournalism.  anews ethics.  aremediation.1 aAkrofi-Quarcoo, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarrera, Jorge, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBowler, Derek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurchell, Kenzie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChouliaraki, Lilie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEscudero, Carolina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFielding, Stephanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForrester, Tamika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKang, Inkyu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLau, Andree, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLithgow, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLithgow, Michael, eeditor